The Long-Dated Maturities

The real fear in Hollywood these days is what=E2=80=99s coming=E2=80=94and =
is, in fact, already here=E2=80=94from the tech companies, such as Apple, A=
mazon, and Google, to say nothing of Netflix. Apple, Amazon, and Google hav=
e infinite resources, of course, and their focus is not on creating traditi=
onal Hollywood content, per se, so much as getting customers into their eco=
systems so that they can sell them what they really want to sell them. Zaz =
is probably worried that the trillion-dollar tech companies, studying their=
 algorithms and their data streams, will be the only survivors of the conte=
nt wars=E2=80=94even if it=E2=80=99s just a peripheral business for them=E2=
=80=94while the traditional Hollywood players, who care about movie quality=
 and the shared experience of moviegoing, are kicked to the curb, suffering=
 from mounting losses and fewer degrees of M&A freedom.

Maybe this is just a real-time example of what economist Joseph Schumpeter =
meant when he described the =E2=80=9Ccreative destruction=E2=80=9D inherent=
 in capitalism. The market isn=E2=80=99t exactly seeing these traditional m=
ediacos as survivors. As I said above, WBD=E2=80=99s stock is down 65 perce=
nt since Zaz formed the company. Disney=E2=80=99s stock is down 32 percent =
in the past five years. Comcast=E2=80=99s stock is down a more modest 9 per=
cent in the past five years, thanks probably to its lucrative cable and the=
me park businesses. Paramount Global=E2=80=99s stock is down 77 percent in =
the past five years, and that=E2=80=99s after the Ellison buyout agreement.=
 Meanwhile, Netflix=E2=80=99s stock is up 101 percent in the past five year=
s=E2=80=94Bill Ackman should never have sold out=E2=80=94Apple=E2=80=99s st=
ock is up 342 percent in the past five years, and on and on. It=E2=80=99s t=
ruly a tale of winners and losers.

And yet, I think Zaz still cares about creativity, and that=E2=80=99s what =
prompted his comments at Sun
Valley. I think he=E2=80=99s fighting to save the structure of the old-fash=
ioned movie studio system. It might well be a losing battle, whether or not=
 Trump wins, but Zaz still has some time, given the free cash flow WBD is n=
ow generating and the long-dated maturities on the WBD debt stack. As Zaz i=
s fond of saying to his team at WBD, =E2=80=9COur job isn=E2=80=99t to do w=
hat Wall Street thinks is right. Our job isn=E2=80=99t to make Hollywood ha=
ppy. Our job is to build a great creative company and do what we think is r=
ight to make this company successful for the future. And if people are unha=
ppy or people don=E2=80=99t like you and don=E2=80=99t like me, you know, t=
hat=E2=80=99s okay.=E2=80=9D

In the final scene in Moneyball, we learn that Beane turned down Henry=E2=
=80=99s offer to become the Red Sox general manager. He stayed with the Oak=
land A=E2=80=99s, which all these years later still haven=E2=80=99t won ano=
ther World Series. Two years later, though, using Beane=E2=80=99s philosoph=
y, or some of it anyway, the Red Sox
finally won the World Series for the first time in 86 years. No wonder Zaz =
likes that movie and shows it to his direct reports. It has a happy ending,=
 sort of.

