bb38e6723be2d8" style=3D"color:#d40000;text-decoration:none;font-weight:bol=
d" class=3D"sdf">noted</a></u>: BofA Securities analyst <b>Jessica Reif Ehr=
lich</b>=E2=80=99s report that WBD=E2=80=99s =E2=80=9Ccurrent composition a=
s a consolidated public company is not working,=E2=80=9D and a <i>Financial=
 Times </i>piece that mysteriously entered the inner monologue of WBD leade=
rship, suggesting various spin-off options, like sending the cable assets o=
ff to sea with a bunch of debt, and focusing on a streamer-and-studio growt=
hco. (I don=E2=80=99t see it, personally, for the simple reason that there =
would be a debt-holder meltdown, even if WBD=E2=80=99s cov-lite loans might=
 permit the rearrangement of the security packages.)<br/><br/>If the govern=
ment won=E2=80=99t let companies like WBD do any deals, then what choice do=
es Zaz
have to try to create shareholder value other than by breaking up his own c=
ompany? Which, I have to say, kind of defeats the purpose behind putting it=
 together in the first place. (Maybe I=E2=80=99m biased as an old Wall Stre=
et M&amp;A guy. I know most M&amp;A deals don=E2=80=99t work out, but I usu=
ally respect the industrial logic for doing them.) In any event, since Zaz =
made his comment in Sun Valley, the WBD stock has had one of its best runs =
in a long, long time=E2=80=94up 18 percent in the past week, although it=E2=
=80=99s still down 65 percent from the start of this experiment in April 20=
22.<br/></td>
