          <td style=3D"padding-bottom: 36px; color: #000000; font-size: 16p=
x; line-height: 30px; margin-top: 0; margin-bottom: 0;">This isn=E2=80=99t =
investment advice, but I don=E2=80=99t get the sense that Zaz is looking to=
 break anything up. Instead, I think he=E2=80=99s going to be partner-curio=
us until he can pull the trigger on something larger. I think that=E2=80=99=
s what he wants to do, and I think it=E2=80=99s what he has to do, too. <br=
/><br/>I=E2=80=99m sure, for instance, that Zaz could have done the Paramou=
nt deal if he=E2=80=99d wanted to=E2=80=94he probably would have had the fi=
nancial firepower to get it done, and his banks would have supported him by=
 providing the needed financing. Of course, that=E2=80=99s not the same as =
saying that the WBD-Paramount Global deal would have been advisable=E2=80=
=94quite the opposite, in fact. (A conclusion that Zaz no doubt reached him=
self.) As I have written before, hoovering up Paramount=E2=80=99s $12 billi=
on of debt would have been the <i>last</i> thing WBD needed after spending =
the last
two years reducing its debt load by $15 billion, to say nothing of inheriti=
ng Paramount=E2=80=99s other problems, such as the $2 billion in losses at =
Paramount+ and the declining fortunes of its linear TV businesses. <br/><br=
/>But all of that aside=E2=80=94and that=E2=80=99s not to minimize those ch=
allenges=E2=80=94it has to give a C.E.O. pause to pull the trigger on a dea=
l like Paramount when he or she knows that regulators are going to tie the =
company up in knots for 18 months while the deal gets analyzed and then may=
 or may not approve it. Who needs that hassle? And what board of directors =
will underwrite that risk? Things are moving way too fast in the land of Bi=
g Media and streaming to be bogged down for 18 months for <i>any</i> reason=
=2E <br/><br/>So no wonder Zaz is plead=
ing for some relief and a faster decis=
ion process, and a signal that such deals are at least within the realm of =
possibility. And maybe some relief is coming, in this <i>very specific area=
</i>, in the form of a second
<b>Trump</b> administration. I suspect that=E2=80=99s what, say, Google is =
counting on with its likely $23 billion acquisition of Wiz. It seems unlike=
ly that Google would attempt that deal if it didn=E2=80=99t think the antit=
rust and regulatory environment in Washington was closer to being changed t=
han not.<br/><br/>So what=E2=80=99s a Zaz to do? In the absence of being ab=
le to do material M&amp;A deals, I think what we=E2=80=99re seeing now in H=
ollywood is a new age of collaboration and partnerships. That=E2=80=99s loo=
king like the only way these big players who have brought us billions of do=
llars of fresh streaming content can hope to stem the losses they are facin=
g. That=E2=80=99s why WBD, Disney, and Fox joined together to create their =
sports bundle, Venu, in May, and why Zaz pursued the Hulu, Max, and Disney+=
 bundle (the details of which are still to come). I wouldn=E2=80=99t be sur=
prised to see Paramount+ somehow, at some point, come together with Max. Ho=
w else is <b>David</b> <b>Ellison</b> and RedBird Capital
going to get the $2 billion in losses at Paramount+ off the Paramount Globa=
l balance sheet? I know <b>Larry</b> <b>Ellison</b> is one of the richest m=
en in the world, but even he can=E2=80=99t countenance a business that lose=
s $2 billion a year. <br/><br/>I=E2=80=99m sure on some level that Zaz woul=
d like to be able to buy Fox Corporation from the <b>Murdochs</b>. If he di=
d, or could, he=E2=80=99d get a coveted package of NFL games and a bunch of=
 decent Fox programming. (He=E2=80=99d have to do something with Fox News a=
nd Fox Business, I suspect, given how poorly they would combine with CNN, f=
or a variety of reasons.) But unless something changes in Washington, he wo=
n=E2=80=99t be able to do that deal. What he will be able to do, and appare=
ntly has done, is get in a room with <b>Bob Iger </b>and <b>Lachlan</b> <b>=
Murdoch</b>=E2=80=94people he knows, likes, and trusts, and who know, like,=
 and trust him=E2=80=94and cut a deal to create Venu. Nor would I be surpri=
sed to see Zaz collaborate more frequently with
<b>Neal</b> <b>Mohan</b>, the C.E.O. of YouTube, to bring WBD=E2=80=99s con=
tent to YouTube=E2=80=99s audience. They already have the Sunday Ticket-Max=
 deal together and collaborated on a roughly $20 billion bid for the NBA ri=
ghts package that seems to be headed to Amazon. (It didn=E2=80=99t work out=
 in the end.) The Mohan/Zaz friendship is real, at least if their time toge=
ther in Sun Valley is any indication. This is the kind of thing the remaini=
ng Hollywood players have to do since the regulatory environment is so diff=
icult for them. They are collaborating out of necessity; it=E2=80=99s akin =
to a presidential executive order when the dynamics in Congress prevent the=
 passage of legislation.<br/></td>
         </tr>
