          <td style=3D"padding-bottom: 36px; color: #000000; font-size: 16p=
x; line-height: 30px; margin-top: 0; margin-bottom: 0;">The real fear in Ho=
llywood these days is what=E2=80=99s coming=E2=80=94and is, in fact, alread=
y here=E2=80=94from the tech companies, such as Apple, Amazon, and Google, =
to say nothing of Netflix. Apple, Amazon, and Google have infinite resource=
s, of course, and their focus is not on creating traditional Hollywood cont=
ent, <i>per se</i>, so much as getting customers into their ecosystems so t=
hat they can sell them what they <i>really</i> want to sell them. Zaz is pr=
obably worried that the trillion-dollar tech companies, studying their algo=
rithms and their data streams, will be the only survivors of the content wa=
rs=E2=80=94even if it=E2=80=99s just a peripheral business for them=E2=80=
=94while the traditional Hollywood players, who care about movie quality an=
d the shared experience of moviegoing, are kicked to the curb, suffering fr=
om mounting losses and fewer degrees of M&amp;A freedom.
<br/><br/>Maybe this is just a real-time example of what economist <b>Josep=
h Schumpeter</b> meant when he described the =E2=80=9Ccreative destruction=
=E2=80=9D inherent in capitalism. The market isn=E2=80=99t exactly seeing t=
hese traditional mediacos as survivors. As I said above, WBD=E2=80=99s stoc=
k is down 65 percent since Zaz formed the company. Disney=E2=80=99s stock i=
s down 32 percent in the past five years. Comcast=E2=80=99s stock is down a=
 more modest 9 percent in the past five years, thanks probably to its lucra=
tive cable and theme park businesses. Paramount Global=E2=80=99s stock is d=
own 77 percent in the past five years, and that=E2=80=99s after the Ellison=
 buyout agreement. Meanwhile, Netflix=E2=80=99s stock is up 101 percent in =
the past five years=E2=80=94<b>Bill Ackman</b> should never have sold out=
=E2=80=94Apple=E2=80=99s stock is up 342 percent in the past five years, an=
d on and on. It=E2=80=99s truly a tale of winners and losers. <br/><br/>And=
 yet, I think Zaz still cares about creativity, and that=E2=80=99s what pro=
mpted his comments at Sun
Valley. I think he=E2=80=99s fighting to save the structure of the old-fash=
ioned movie studio system. It might well be a losing battle, whether or not=
 Trump wins, but Zaz still has some time, given the free cash flow WBD is n=
ow generating and the long-dated maturities on the WBD debt stack. As Zaz i=
s fond of saying to his team at WBD, =E2=80=9COur job isn=E2=80=99t to do w=
hat Wall Street thinks is right. Our job isn=E2=80=99t to make Hollywood ha=
ppy. Our job is to build a great creative company and do what we think is r=
ight to make this company successful for the future. And if people are unha=
ppy or people don=E2=80=99t like you and don=E2=80=99t like me, you know, t=
hat=E2=80=99s okay.=E2=80=9D<br/><br/>In the final scene in <i>Moneyball</i=
>, we learn that Beane turned down Henry=E2=80=99s offer to become the Red =
Sox general manager. He stayed with the Oakland A=E2=80=99s, which all thes=
e years later still haven=E2=80=99t won another World Series. Two years lat=
er, though, using Beane=E2=80=99s philosophy, or some of it anyway, the Red=
 Sox
finally won the World Series for the first time in 86 years. No wonder Zaz =
likes that movie and shows it to his direct reports. It has a happy ending,=
 sort of.<br/></td>
